article.description:
Temeka Johnson scored all 15 of her
points in the first half Saturday, leading undefeated LSU (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 2 AP) to
a 91-40 victory over Southwest Texas Saturday.
article.headline: Tigers off to best start since 1996-97
article.linkText: Tigers stay undefeated after rout of Southwest Texas State
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Now comes the tough part of the schedule
for  LSU  (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 2 AP).  The Tigers (9-0) beat Southwest Texas 91-40 on Saturday in
another easy non-conference win.

 LSU has played only two ranked
teams and hosts No. 22 Texas next Saturday and No. 16 Penn State on
Jan. 4. It opens Southeastern Conference play at undefeated Auburn
on Jan. 9.

	   "I think we're tired of playing teams that we can easily
beat," said Temeka Johnson, who led LSU in scoring with 15 points,
all coming in the first half. "We're ready for the competition."

	   On Saturday, LSU got more rebounds than the Bobcats (1-7), but
barely: 37-35. DeTrina White led the Tigers with five rebounds.

	   But LSU has its strengths, and quick scoring and a strong bench
made the difference. In the first half, LSU used 13 players and put
the game away.

	   The Tigers opened with a 10-0 run in which White hit a jumper
off the opening tip and Aiysha Smith and Seimone Augustus each
scored four points.

	   Southwest Texas cut the lead to 15-7 on two jumpers by Tori
Talbert and a 3-pointer by Julie Brooks. After a timeout, LSU went
on a 16-2 run to give LSU a 31-11 lead. An 8-0 run by the Tigers
extended their lead to 55-23 with 3:39 left.

	   LSU went on a 14-2 run over the final 5:41 of the first to go
into the break with a 61-25 lead on 69 percent shooting.

	   "We came out with great intensity," coach Sue Gunter said. "I
thought our bench picked up the tempo and brought even more
energy."

	   LSU scored the first 15 points of the second half in just over
six minutes.

	   Alcise Johnson and Brooks each had 10 points for Southwest
Texas. The Bobcats shot 26 percent and turned the ball over 29
times.
	   
"We're now at the foot of the mountain, and we have to start
climbing," Gunter said.
